<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
  The <a href="/backlog/1451-library-adapter-watch-keep-incumbent-lib-adapters-current/">library-adapter
  watch (#1451)</a> surfaced a public-positioning decision: WE should publish a
  <strong>capability × impl compatibility table</strong> — one row per WE
  <a href="/protocols/">protocol</a> / <a href="/intents/">intent</a>, one column per implementation
  (native · FUI · Floating UI · Mousetrap · TanStack · focus-trap · …), each cell a support tier. This is
  the existing native-substrate matrix (<code>src/_data/capabilityMatrix.json</code>)
  <em>broadened from native substrates to incumbent libraries</em> and surfaced as a public
  <a href="/capabilities/">catalog</a> mirroring <code>/protocols/</code> and <code>/intents/</code>. Its
  strategic purpose: make it self-evident that <strong>WE is a standard for the web in general, not a
  front-end for one library</strong> — every lib, FUI included, is just a column. The one genuine fork:
  <strong>how does FUI appear in that table — a peer column, or a privileged "reference / recommended impl"
  column?</strong>
</p>

<h2>Finding 1 — the rendering mechanism already exists; this broadens the rows and decides the positioning</h2>
<p>
  <code>src/_data/capabilityMatrix.json</code> (lines 8–66) is the registered capability-adapter table:
  one row per impl, each declaring a capability-id → 3-state tier map
  (<code>native-ok</code> / <code>polyfill-ok</code> / <code>capability-hard</code>, lines 3–7). Today it
  holds <strong>native substrates only</strong> — <code>face</code> (lines 9–36) and
  <code>base-select</code> (lines 37–65, <code>native:true</code>). And <code>src/capabilities.njk</code>
  (lines 21–39) <strong>already renders that matrix as a grid with one column per impl</strong>. So the
  column-per-impl compat-grid mechanism is built; #1450 broadens the <em>rows</em> (native substrate →
  incumbent lib — Floating UI, Mousetrap, TanStack, FUI) and decides the public <em>positioning</em> of
  FUI's column. "Adding a new impl is a single-row registration"
  (<a href="/backlog/206-capability-adapter-registration-table/">#206</a>).
</p>

<h2>Finding 2 — every neutral compat artifact lists impls as peer columns, none flagged "official"</h2>
<p>
  Treating standards bodies as <strong>upstream collaborators, not competitors</strong> (align, don't
  compete), the canonical multi-implementation compat artifacts converge on one shape: a feature-row ×
  impl-column grid with per-cell support tiers and <strong>no column flagged official.</strong>
</p>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
  <thead><tr><th>Artifact</th><th>Rows</th><th>Columns</th><th>Privileged column?</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>MDN Browser Compat Data (BCD)</td><td>~15,000 web features</td><td>browsers / JS runtimes</td><td><strong>No</strong> — every engine a peer</td></tr>
    <tr><td>caniuse.com</td><td>per-feature</td><td>per-engine</td><td><strong>No</strong> (merged BCD: ~500 → ~10,500 tables)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>wpt.fyi (Web Platform Tests)</td><td>per-test</td><td>per-engine</td><td><strong>No</strong> — pass-rate %, strength earned</td></tr>
    <tr><td>ECMAScript / Kangax tables</td><td>per-feature</td><td>per-engine/runtime</td><td><strong>No</strong></td></tr>
    <tr><td>OpenFeature providers</td><td>per-technology</td><td>per-provider</td><td><strong>No</strong> (coverage %; see Finding 3)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>W3C/WHATWG process</td><td>per-feature</td><td>"N independent impls"</td><td><strong>No</strong> — independence is the bar</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
</we-data-table>
<p>
  BCD + caniuse are the web's most-consulted compat surface, and no engine column is ever marked
  "recommended" — support is shown, not editorialized. <strong>wpt.fyi</strong> shows per-engine
  pass-rates side by side: a green engine is green because it <em>passes the tests</em>, not because the
  dashboard endorses it — strength <strong>earned and visible</strong>, never declared. That is exactly
  default (A)'s model: FUI's coverage breadth shows as the column green across the most rows.
</p>

<h2>Finding 3 — OpenFeature: even a standard with a reference impl keeps the matrix neutral</h2>
<p>
  OpenFeature is the instructive near-counter-example. It <em>does</em> bless a reference implementation
  (<code>flagd</code>), yet its provider table still lists every provider with a coverage % (DevCycle 76%,
  flagd 53%, ConfigCat 47% — peer rows). The reference impl is named in <em>docs / concepts</em>, not by
  privileging its row in the support matrix. So even a standard that has a reference impl keeps the
  <strong>compat matrix itself neutral</strong> — the "recommended" pointer lives in editorial
  getting-started prose, not the grid. This is precisely #1450's recommended split: ratify A and put any
  adoption pointer in a clearly-editorial place (the ~20% residual). W3C/WHATWG reinforce it structurally —
  a feature is normative only with <strong>≥2 independent conforming implementations</strong>; the process
  sources status from caniuse / wpt.fyi annotations and marks single-impl features "at risk." No impl is
  ever "official"; independence is the whole point.
</p>

<h2>Classification (per-fork pass)</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Layer / shape</strong> — <strong>not</strong> a Protocol or an Intent. A
    <strong>public catalog surface</strong> over <code>src/_data/capabilityMatrix.json</code> (a
    rendering / positioning decision), mirroring <code>/protocols/</code> and <code>/intents/</code>
    (auto-render from JSON). New surface = page + nav + authoring note + validator.</li>
  <li><strong>Principle already settled; only positioning open</strong> — impl-neutrality (FUI is one
    conforming implementation; the capabilityMatrix resolver-impl rule) is statute in
    <a href="/docs/agent/platform-decisions.md">platform-decisions.md</a> (lines 104, 264). #1450 does
    <em>not</em> re-open the principle — the single open question is the positioning of FUI's column
    (peer vs privileged).</li>
  <li><strong>Ownership</strong> — the table + contracts + conformance vectors are <strong>WE</strong>;
    the impl columns reference FUI-owned and third-party-owned adapter impls (locus stays with the
    impl), mirroring #1451's WE-coordinates / FUI-locus split.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The prepared fork</h2>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>A — FUI is a peer column</strong> <em>(recommended, ~80%)</em>. FUI is listed exactly like
    every other impl; its strength is <em>earned and visible</em> as the column green across the most
    rows, never declared by status. Matches every neutral compat artifact surveyed (BCD, caniuse,
    wpt.fyi, OpenFeature) and aligns native-first + minimize-lock-in.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>B — FUI is a privileged "reference / recommended impl" column</strong>
    <em>(Rejected — anti-pattern)</em>. Re-introduces the exact single-lib perception the table exists to
    dispel; the lone anti-pattern across the survey, and conflicts with minimize-lock-in.
  </li>
</ul>
<p>
  <strong>Recommended: A.</strong> <em>(~80%. Residual: a curated "recommended impl" can lower adoption
  friction — but, per OpenFeature, that belongs in a clearly-editorial getting-started pointer, not in a
  neutrality artifact's columns; the reference-impl idea is not wrong, it is mis-placed if it privileges a
  matrix column.)</em>
</p>

